### ||| AUT 754 -
# وعن سعيد بن الحارث أنه سأل جابرا رضي الله عنه عن الوضوء مما مست النار
~~. فقال : لا قد كنا زمن النبي صلى الله عليه و سلم لا نجد مثل ذلك الطعام
~~إلا قليلا فإذا نحن وجدناه لم يكن لنا مناديل إلا أكفنا وسواعدنا وأقدامنا
~~ثم نصلي ولا نتوضأ . رواه البخاري 754. sa`id bin al-harith reported: i
~~asked jabir (may allah be pleased with him) whether it was obligatory to
~~make wudu' for salat (prayer) after eating cooked food. he said: "no,
~~because in the lifetime of messenger of allah (pbuh), such food was
~~rarely available. we had no handkerchiefs, so when we ate such food we
~~would wipe our fingers against our palms, forearms or (the sole of our)
~~feet, and would offer salat without fresh wudu' (for prayer).'' [al-
~~bukhari]. commentary: there are three points in this hadith. first, the
~~life of the companions was simple, divested of all kinds of luxuries and
~~comforts. they lived on whatever was available to them. second, a man's
~~ablution is not nullified by eating a cooked food. in the early days of
~~islam, this command was put into practice but later it was cancelled.
~~third, if a handkerchief, or a towel or water is not available, a man
~~can (after taking a meal) clean his mouth and hands with his palms and
~~wrists so that his clothes will not be smeared during salat (prayer).
~~PageV01P0958

